{{Infobox academic |name=Adia Benton |image= |birth_date=1977 |residence=United States |nationality=American |occupation=anthropologist, professor |awards=Rachel Carson Award |education=Brown University, Emory University, Harvard University |discipline=medical anthropology, science and technology studies |workplaces=Northwestern University}}
'''Adia Benton''' is an American cultural and medical anthropologist. She won the 2017 [[Rachel Carson Prize (academic book prize)|Rachel Carson Prize]] for her book ''HIV Exceptionalism: Development Through Disease in Sierra Leone''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/903645936|title=HIV exceptionalism : development through disease in Sierra Leone|first=Aida|last=Benton |isbn=9781452943848|location=Minneapolis|oclc=903645936}}</ref> from the [[Society for Social Studies of Science]]. She is currently an Assistant Professor of Anthropology and [[African studies|African Studies]] at [[Northwestern University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.4sonline.org/prizes/carson17|title=4S Prizes {{!}} Society for Social Studies of Science|website=www.4sonline.org|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref>
