ar College|website=vcencyclopedia.vassar.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-10-01}}</ref> |- style="vertical-align: top;" !scope="row"| {{sortname|Eleanor|Maccoby}} |1917– |American |American Psychologist and current Stanford professor who studies various aspects of family psychology. She also researches a considerable amount on gender studies and gender discrimination. | align="center" |<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2014-01-31|title=Inside the Psychologist’s Studio: Eleanor Maccoby|url=https://www.psychologicalscience.org/observer/eleanor-maccoby-itps|journal=APS Observer|language=en-US|volume=27|issue=2}}</ref> |- style="vertical-align: top;" !scope="row"| {{sortname|Brenda|Milner}} |1918– |British |A British [[neuropsychologist]] who earned her bachelor's and master's degrees at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]] and PhD from McGill University. Her career included researching about war effort, influenced by [[World War II]] at the time, and studying about epileptic patients. She continues to work today and is currently studying about the brain's hemispheres and its relationship. | align="center" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.feministvoices.com/Brenda-Milner/|title=Brenda Milner - Psychology's Feminist Voices|last=Summers|first=Carol|website=www.feministvoices.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref> |- style="vertical-align: top;" !scope="row"| {{sortname|Maria|Montessori}} | 1870–1952 |Italian | [[Italy|Italian]] physician and educator best known for the [[Montessori education|philosophy of education that bears her name]], and her writing on scientific [[pedagogy]]. | align="center" |<ref>Maria Montessori. (n.d.). In Feminist Voices online. Retrieved from http://www.feministvoices.com/maria-montessori/</ref> |- style="vertical-align: top;" !scope="row"| {{sortname|Carolyn R.|Payton}} |1925–2001 |American |A well-known professor of psychology and a very involved member of the [[American Psychological Association]]. She was also the first woman dire